'''Miran Božovič''' (born August 12, 1957) is a [[Slovenia]]n [[philosopher]] and [[psychoanalyst]], associated with the [[Ljubljana school of psychoanalysis]].
Božovič was born in [[Ljubljana]]. He holds a degree in [[comparative literature]] and philosophy from the [[University of Ljubljana]], and a PhD in philosophy. He teaches [[early modern philosophy]] at the Faculty of Arts of the University of Ljubljana.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ff.uni-lj.si/oddelki/filo/osebje/bozovic.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-01-13 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090228104855/http://www.ff.uni-lj.si/oddelki/filo/osebje/bozovic.htm |archivedate=2009-02-28 |df= }}</ref>
Božovič has written on several controversial subjects, including [[Jeremy Bentham|Bentham]]'s concept of [[panopticon]], the conceptualizations of the body in early modern philosophy, and the influence of traditional [[exorcist]] notions on [[Descartes]]' philosophy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fi.zrc-sazu.si/?q=node/466|title=Integralna obremenjenost prodnih ravnin|website=fi.zrc-sazu.si}}</ref>
